(34, 2, 3, 'High Current MOSFETs: A Necessity in Power Design', '       In today\'s automotive and industrial electronics, low-voltage MOSFETs are increasingly in demand for high power. For applications such as motor drives, power output in the kilowatt range is now required. This, together with current module space constraints, means that the need for more power is being passed on to components, specifically MOSFETs. To get the best performance out of power MOSFETs and maintain device reliability over the required operating life, careful consideration of design requirements and understanding of maximum ratings in circuit design are required.\r\n\r\n      The gate, source, and drain terminals of the MOSFET are all connected together. Any of these terminals, labeled IG, IS, and ID, can allow current to flow. Engineers and electrical designers must thoroughly understand the essential capabilities, constraints, and environmental conditions in order to select the best MOSFET for the application. ID is affected by MOSFET characteristics such as bond wires and copper clips, current spreading, and package thermals (max). The ability of a MOSFET to withstand even very high working currents, as well as its high performance, robustness, and dependability, are all important characteristics. The LFPAK package is intended for a smaller footprint and higher power density than older metal cable packages such as the D2PAK for today\'s high-power automotive applications with space constraints. It delivers outstanding performance and durability and is intended for today\'s high-power automotive applications with space constraints.', 'mosfets.jpg', '2021-12-07'),
(35, 4, 3, '3D and VR Models in Civil Engineering Education: Construction, Rehabilitation &amp; Maintenance', '         In terms of educational validity, a school of engineering can be reasonably expected to constantly update computational resources that are frequently used in the professions. Virtual reality (VR) technology could be used as a supplement to three-dimensional (3D) modeling, resulting in improved communication in vocational training, education, and professional practice. Models related to the construction process were created using 3D modeling and virtual reality techniques.\r\n\r\n        The 3D models developed to aid rehabilitation design emerge as an important tool for monitoring structural anomalies and assisting decisions based on visual analyses of alternative solutions. The VR model developed to aid in the management of lighting systems in buildings allows for the visual and interactive transmission of information related to the physical behavior of the elements, defined as a function of time.\r\n\r\n     These applications enable the visual simulation of the physical progression of each type of work, as well as the study of the necessary equipment and how it functions on the job site. Students benefit from the introduction of CAD and VR techniques in school because it prepares them to view these technologies as important supports later in their professional careers.', '3d and vr.jpg', '2021-12-07');

